To generate a 3‐token string from S with a CNF grammar, one branch of the top split must yield exactly 1 terminal and the other exactly 2 terminals.  But in every S‐production

  S → NT49 NT40  
  S → NT42 NT20  
  S → NT21 NT74  
  S → NT17 NT47  

neither NT49, NT42, NT21 nor NT17 can produce a single terminal (none of them has a direct terminal rule).  Hence each child must produce at least 2 terminals, so S can generate only strings of length ≥4.  A 3‐token string is impossible.

Since no NT covers positions 5–6, no larger span that includes those two terminals can be built, and in particular S cannot appear over the whole 1–6 span.  Hence the string is not in the language.
